Renowned British actress Diana Rigg, known for her prolific performances on the big screen and on stage, died on Thursday at the age of 82. Her daughter Rachael Stirling said Rigg had been diagnosed with cancer in March and "spent her last months joyfully reflecting on her extraordinary life, full of love, laughter and a deep pride in her profession." "My Beloved Ma died peacefully in her sleep early this morning, at home, surrounded by family," Stirling said. "I will miss her beyond words." Read more: James Bond: Born in Germany? Rigg was best known for her ability to feel at home acting for both theater and the big screen. She won several Emmy, Tony and Bafta awards throughout her long acting career. She was best known for her roles in 1960s cult TV classic "The Avengers," Bond flick "On Her Majesty's Secret Service" and contemporary hit series "Game of Thrones." However, some of her best roles were off the big screen and played out on stage. Read more: Aston Martin is recreating James Bond's 'Goldfinger' DB5 Diana Rigg would go on to play as Olenna Tyrell in the hit HBO series "Game of Thrones" Rigg made her debut at the Royal Shakespeare Company in 1959 and would go on to feature in several theater performances. "Rigg's combination of force of personality, beauty, courage and sheer emotional power, made her a great classical actress — one of an astonishing generation of British stage performers," said theater and opera director Jonathan Kent. "Her dazzling wit and that inimitable voice made her an unforgettable leading figure in British theater." Read more: Game of Thrones' worst war criminals ranked by Red Cross Those who worked with Rigg remarked on her charisma and kindness ls/msh (Reuters, AFP)